<p>I will start off with my personal favorite addition, for itâ€™s potential use in leetCode style coding challanges involving string manipulation.
Java 11 introduces new string methods: repeat(int), lines(), strip(), stripLeading(), stripTailing(), and isBlank()</p>

<p>Letâ€™s start with an example from <a href="https://howtodoinjava.com/java11/repeat-string-n-times/">howtodoinjava</a> . It shows how we can create a string that is composed of repeats of some substring.</p>

<pre><code class="language-Java">String repeat () example
public class StringRepeat 
{
    public static void main(String[] args) 
    {
        String str = "Abc";
 
        System.out.println( str.repeat(3) );
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Example 1: Java 11 String class creates a repeated string</p>

<p>Program output-</p>

<p>Console
AbcAbcAbc</p>

<p>From this, letâ€™s construct our own examples referencing <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/allclasses.html">the documentation</a> and Example 1.
Java String lines() does not return number of lines as you might expect, but returns a Stream of Strings</p>

<pre><code class="language-Java">import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.stream.Stream;

public class StringLines {

    public static void main(String args[]){
        String str = "Abc\nAbc\nAbc\n"; 
 
        Stream&lt;String&gt; lines = str.lines();
        lines.forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Example 2: Java 11 String class prints all lines of a string</p>

<p>Referncing another lines() <a href="https://howtodoinjava.com/java11/string-to-stream-of-lines/">example</a> example, letâ€™s explore strip() and itâ€™s derivatives with simple error handling, for good measure.</p>

<p>import java.io.IOException;</p>

<pre><code class="language-Java">public class StringStrip {

    public static void main(String args[]){
        
        try
        {
	    String str = "    leading - tailing     ";
            System.out.println(str);            
            System.out.print("String:\n");
            System.out.print("strip:\n");
            System.out.print(str.strip());
            System.out.print("stripTailing:\n");
            System.out.print(str.stripTrailing());
            System.out.print("stripLeading:\n");
            System.out.print(str.stripLeading());
        } 
        catch (Exception e) 
        {
            e.printStackTrace(); // NetBeans hint: throwable printStackTrace should be removed...
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>

<p>Now letâ€™s wrap up with what might be the simplest one: isBlank(). Unlike isEmpty(), isBlank() does not check stringLength.</p>

<pre><code class="language-Java">	Let String str = " A non-whitespace character or two  "
	str.isEmpty() - FALSE
	str.isBlank() - FALSE
	
	str.isEmpty() - FALSE
	str.isBlank() - TRUE
	
	Let String str = ""
	str.isEmpty() - TRUE
	str.isBlank() - TRUE
</code></pre>

